{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Getting Started\n",
    "\n",
    "This guide will make use of the dataset generated with the Commercial Modular Aero-Propulsion System Simulation (C-MAPSS) dynamical model.\n",
    "The dataset consists of multiple multivariate time series. Each data set is further divided into training and test subsets. Each time series is from a different engine - i.e., the data can be considered to be from a fleet of engines of the same type. Each engine starts with different degrees of initial wear and manufacturing variation which is unknown to the user. This wear and variation are considered normal, i.e., it is not considered a fault condition. There are three operational settings that have a substantial effect on engine performance. These settings are also included in the data. The data are contaminated with sensor noise.\n",
    "\n",
    "The engine is operating normally at the start of each time series and starts to degrade at some point during the series. In the training set, the degradation grows in magnitude until a predefined threshold is reached beyond which it is not preferable to operate the engine. In the test set, the time series ends some time prior to complete degradation. The objective of the competition is to predict the number of operational cycles after the last cycle that the engine will continue to operate properly.\n",
    "\n",
    "The data are provided as a zip-compressed text file with 26 columns of numbers, separated by spaces. Each row is a snapshot of data taken during a single operational cycle; each column is a different variable.\n",
    "\n",
    "Dataset structure\n",
    "\n",
    "* Unit: Engine number [-]\n",
    "* t: time [cycles]\n",
    "* 0p1: operational setting 1\n",
    "* op2: operational setting 2\n",
    "* op3: operational setting 3\n",
    "* s1: Sensor measurement 1\n",
    "* s2: Sensor measurement 2\n",
    "...\n",
    "* s20: sensor measurement 20\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "In the first set of data, there are 100 train trajectories and 100 test trajectories.\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "[1] A. Saxena, M. Ieee, K. Goebel, D. Simon, and N. Eklund, “Damage Propagation Modeling for Aircraft Engine Prognostics,” Response, 2008. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [

    "## Dataset"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The Dataset comes in a space separated tabular file. The functions `process_file_train` and `process_file_test` receive the filename of the dataset file and return a `pd.DataFrame` with the pre-processed data. The `UnitNumber` column is a life identifier."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In order to define a dataset you should subclass `AbstractLivesDataset` and define three methods:\n",
    "\n",
    "  * `__getitem__(self, i)`: This method should return the i-th life \n",
    "  * `nlives(self)`: In this method should return the total number of lives present in the dataset"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "class CMAPSSDataset(AbstractTimeSeriesDataset):\n",
    "    def __init__(self, train=True, model=None):\n",
    "        super().__init__()\n",
    "        if model is not None:\n",
    "            if model not in operation_mode:\n",
    "                raise ValueError(\n",
    "                    f'Invalid model: valid model are {list(operation_mode.keys())}')\n",
    "        if train:\n",
    "            processing_fun = process_file_train\n",
    "        else:\n",
    "            processing_fun = process_file_test\n",
    "        self.lives = []\n",
    "        for engine in engines:\n",
    "            if model is not None and engine != model:\n",
    "                continue\n",
    "            for _, g in processing_fun(engine).groupby('UnitNumber'):\n",
    "                g.drop(columns=['UnitNumber'], inplace=True)\n",
    "                self.lives.append(g)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    def get_time_series(self, i):\n",
    "        return self.lives[i]\n",
    "\n",
    "    def number_of_samples_of_time_series(self):\n",
    "        return len(self.lives)\n",
    "    \n",
    "    @property\n",
    "    def n_time_series(self):\n",
    "        return len(self.lives)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "train_dataset = CMAPSSDataset(train=True, model='FD001')\n",
    "validation_dataset = CMAPSSDataset(train=False, model='FD001')"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "### Missing values\n",
    "Usually, the information of sensors is incomplete and this causes numerous missing values in the features. This library provides some useful functions to analyse the proportion of the missing values for each feature for each life. In some cases, if the feature values are missing in multiple lives, that feature can be discarded.\n",
    "\n",
    "Luckily in the NASA dataset, we don't have any missing values:"
   ]

    "### Variance\n",
    "Another possibility is that sensors do not vary equally in a diverse set of lives. Another function obtains information about the variance of each feature per each life. If a feature variance is zero in many lives, maybe it is a good idea to remove it.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the NASA dataset, we can see that some of the features have a zero variance in some of the lives."
   ]

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Transformers"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Transformers are defined using an API similar to the keras functional API.\n",
    "\n",
    "Two tarnsformer pipelines have to be defined:\n",
    "* How the data is going to be transformed\n",
    "    * This transformer invovles selecting and transforming and generating features\n",
    "* How the target is going to be transformed\n",
    "    * This transformer involves selecting and transforming the target"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Functional API"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Following the literature, the future that addresses this dataset, only a subset of the feature are going to be used to fit our model."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "['SensorMeasure2',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure3',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure4',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure7',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure8',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure9',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure11',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure12',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure13',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure14',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure15',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure17',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure20',\n",
       " 'SensorMeasure21']"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 11,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "features = [train_dataset[0].columns[i] for i in sensor_indices]\n",
    "features"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The transformation of the input data will be simple, a feature scaling between -1 and 1 and imputing any missing value or non finite."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "functional_pipe = ByNameFeatureSelector(features)\n",
    "functional_pipe = PandasMinMaxScaler((-1,1), robust=False)(functional_pipe)\n",
    "functional_pipe = PandasMeanImputer()(functional_pipe)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "One common approach for handling PM problems is to downplay the early stages of the execution due to the fact that that is harder to detect indication of degradation at the beggining.\n",
    "\n",
    "For this dataset, a piece-wise linear degradation model has been validated to be suitable and effective. In general, the engine unit works normally in the early age and degrades linearly afterwards. It is assumed to have a constant RUL label in the initial period.  [1]\n",
    "\n",
    "[1] Li, X., Ding, Q., & Sun, J. Q. (2018). Remaining useful life estimation in prognostics using deep convolution neural networks. Reliability Engineering & System Safety, 172, 1-11."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "target_pipe = ByNameFeatureSelector(['RUL'])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "functional_transformer = Transformer(\n",
    "    transformerX=functional_pipe,\n",
    "    transformerY=target_pipe)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Fitting the transformer\n",
    "\n",
    "The transformer must be fitted on the dataset."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<temporis.transformation.functional.transformers.Transformer at 0x7f81144b9c70>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 15,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "functional_transformer.fit(train_dataset)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Transforming a life"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 16,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X, y, m = functional_transformer.transform(train_dataset[0])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 17,
   "metadata": {},

       "(192, 14)"
      ]

     "execution_count": 17,
     "metadata": {},

   "execution_count": 18,

     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1224x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(17, 5))\n",
    "ax.plot(X);"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### More complex transformers\n",
    "More complex transformers can also be constructed. For example, we may want to use the raw features but also extract some statistics from a subset of features. In this case, we are going to obtain the kurtosis and the peak coefficient using a rolling window for 3 features. There are a lot of different feature extraction and transformation steps that can be applied. I encourage you to check the documentation to discover more.\n",
    "\n",
    "The number of features we are going to obtain at the end will be the 14 coming from the raw features and 6=2*3 coming for the two statistics computed from the selected subset of size 3."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 19,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<temporis.transformation.functional.transformers.Transformer at 0x7f8114137610>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 19,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "raw_pipe = ByNameFeatureSelector(features)\n",
    "raw_pipe = ForwardFillImputer()(raw_pipe)\n",
    "raw_pipe = PandasMinMaxScaler((-1,1), robust=False, name='raw_scaled')(raw_pipe)\n",
    "\n",
    "transformed_pipe = ByNameFeatureSelector(features[0:3])\n",
    "transformed_pipe = RollingStatisticsPandas(window=15, to_compute=['kurtosis', 'peak'])(transformed_pipe)\n",
    "transformed_pipe = PandasMeanImputer()(transformed_pipe)\n",
    "transformed_pipe = PandasMinMaxScaler((-1,1), robust=False, name='transformed_scaled')(transformed_pipe)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "pipe = Concatenate()([raw_pipe, transformed_pipe])\n",
    "\n",
    "target_pipe = ByNameFeatureSelector(['RUL'])\n",
    "\n",
    "complex_transformer = Transformer(\n",
    "    transformerX=pipe,\n",
    "    transformerY=target_pipe)\n",
    "\n",
    "complex_transformer.fit(train_dataset)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 20,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "X, y, m = complex_transformer.transform(train_dataset[0])"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The number of features as expected is 20 features: 14 from the raw features and 6 from the extracted ones"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 21,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [

    "transformed_ds = train_dataset.map(complex_transformer)\n",
    "X, y, sw = transformed_ds[0]\n",
    "    "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### WindowedDatasetIterator\n",
    "The windowed dataset iterator provides a way of iterating the transformed dataset trough an sliding window. The sample for the i-th element, provides the (window-1) elements of the window. It also provides capabilities to shuffle in diverse ways the how the samples are delivered by the iterator."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 27,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "window = 7\n",
    "iterator = WindowedDatasetIterator(\n",
    "    transformed_ds,\n",
    "    window,\n",
    "    step=1,\n",
    "    output_size=1,\n",
    "    shuffler=NotShuffled())\n",
    "\n",
    "X, y, sw = next(iterator)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Since we are using the functional_transformer that only has 14 feature and a window size of 7 samples. The output of one element of the iterator wil be a matrix ox size (7 x14)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 28,

    "## Batcher"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The batcher class make use of the `WindowedDatasetIterator` to generate batches of samples."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 29,
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "window = 25\n",
    "batch_size = 66\n",
    "step = 2\n",
    "train_batcher = Batcher.new(transformed_ds,  \n",
    "                            window, \n",
    "                            batch_size, \n",
    "                            step, \n",
    "                            shuffler=NotShuffled())\n",
    "X, y, sw = next(train_batcher)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},

    "    output_size=1,\n",

    "    val_transformed_ds,\n",
    "    window,\n",
